					<source>Add a picked file to the MRU</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="122" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The files that your user picks are often files that they return to repeatedly.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="123" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>So consider adding picked files to your app's MRU as soon as they are picked.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="124" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Here's how.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="125" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207476)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source><pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">StorageItemMostRecentlyUsedList.Add</pc></pc> is overloaded.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="126" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207481)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>In the example, we use <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">Add(IStorageItem, String)</pc></pc> so that we can associate metadata with the file.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="127" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Setting metadata lets you record the item's purpose, for example "profile pic".</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="128" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207480)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>You can also add the file to the MRU without metadata by calling <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">Add(IStorageItem)</pc></pc>.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="129" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>When you add an item to the MRU, the method returns a uniquely identifying string, called a token, which is used to retrieve the item.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="130" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">**</data>
					<data id="id2">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source><pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">Tip</pc>   You'll need the token to retrieve an item from the MRU, so persist it somewhere.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="131" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh465109)</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>For more info about app data, see <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">Managing application data</pc>.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="132" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Use a token to retrieve an item from the MRU</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="133" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Use the retrieval method most appropriate for the item you want to retrieve.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="134" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227171)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
					<data id="id5">[</data>
					<data id="id6">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207486)</data>
					<data id="id7">**</data>
					<data id="id8">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Retrieve a file as a <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">StorageFile</pc></pc> by using <pc dataRefEnd="id6" dataRefStart="id5" id="p3"><pc dataRefEnd="id8" dataRefStart="id7" id="p4">GetFileAsync</pc></pc>.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="135" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227230)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
					<data id="id5">[</data>
					<data id="id6">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207489)</data>
					<data id="id7">**</data>
					<data id="id8">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Retrieve a folder as a <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">StorageFolder</pc></pc> by using <pc dataRefEnd="id6" dataRefStart="id5" id="p3"><pc dataRefEnd="id8" dataRefStart="id7" id="p4">GetFolderAsync</pc></pc>.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="136" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227129)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
					<data id="id5">[</data>
					<data id="id6">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207492)</data>
					<data id="id7">**</data>
					<data id="id8">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Retrieve a generic <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">IStorageItem</pc></pc>, which can represent either a file or folder, by using <pc dataRefEnd="id6" dataRefStart="id5" id="p3"><pc dataRefEnd="id8" dataRefStart="id7" id="p4">GetItemAsync</pc></pc>.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="137" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Here's how to get back the file we just added.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="138" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Here's how to iterate all the entries to get tokens and then items.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="139" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227349)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">AccessListEntryView</pc></pc> lets you iterate entries in the MRU.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="140" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227348)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>These entries are <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">AccessListEntry</pc></pc> structures that contain the token and metadata for an item.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="141" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Removing items from the MRU when it's full</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="142" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>When the MRU's 25-item limit is reached and you try to add a new item, the item that was accessed the longest time ago is automatically removed.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="143" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>So, you never need to remove an item before you add a new one.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="144" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Future-access list</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="145" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>As well as an MRU, your app also has a future-access list.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="146" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>By picking files and folders, your user grants your app permission to access items that might not be accessible otherwise.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="147" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>If you add these items to your future-access list then you'll retain that permission when your app wants to access those items again later.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="148" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207459)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
					<data id="id5">[</data>
					<data id="id6">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207457)</data>
					<data id="id7">**</data>
					<data id="id8">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Your app's future-access list is represented by the <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">StorageItemAccessList</pc></pc> class, which you obtain from the static <pc dataRefEnd="id6" dataRefStart="id5" id="p3"><pc dataRefEnd="id8" dataRefStart="id7" id="p4">StorageApplicationPermissions.FutureAccessList</pc></pc> property.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="149" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>When a user picks an item, consider adding it to your future-access list as well as your MRU.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="150" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207457)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">FutureAccessList</pc></pc> can hold up to 1000 items.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="151" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Remember: it can hold folders as well as files, so that's a lot of folders.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="152" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207457)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The platform never removes items from the <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">FutureAccessList</pc></pc> for you.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="153" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br207497)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>When you reach the 1000-item limit, you can't add another until you make room with the <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">Remove</pc></pc> method.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
